The paper deals with compressed sensing-based single-pixel detectors and proposes an efficient way of using complex-valued and nonbinary noiselet functions for object sampling. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the efficient representation, storage, and transmission of information. Additionally, the paper involves image processing and computer vision techniques, which could place it in the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also mentions real-time generation of binary noiselet-based patterns, which could suggest that it belongs to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category, which deals with the processing and analysis of multimedia data. The paper involves experimental verification of the proposed method, which could place it in the Signal Processing (cs.SP) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with compressed sensing-based single-pixel detectors, which could suggest that it belongs to the Signal and Image Processing (cs.SI) sub-category.
